<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09153c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09153c">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09153c"> 153(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dog&apos;s barking (lions)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Or is it only vegetables, the hunters having failed to kill any game? then she asks him to &ldquo;eat affliction.&rdquo; And must he refuse her invitation? then the polite formula is: &ldquo;I am not refusing.&rdquo; And are the <mark>lions roaring</mark> out on the plain? then she says, &ldquo;<mark>The dogs are barking</mark>, sir.&rdquo; All super-correct, all absurdly polite, and (this is the point!) all &ldquo;highbrow&rdquo; speech in clean contradiction to her illiterate appearance. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 119</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
